    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically someone else just holds the money so nobody gets scammed. who actually manages the account? like is it a bank or some specific person i need to talk to?&nbsp;",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, exactly! In Toronto, the escrow account is usually managed by a specialized escrow company or a title insurance company, though sometimes the real estate lawyers acting for you or the seller handle it. You don't need to manage it yourself; the professionals in the background are the ones ensuring the funds stay safe until the final signature.\n\nIt's a bit like hiring a very strict, very wealthy family of goblins to guard your treasure chest. You can't just walk in and grab the gold; the goblins have to verify that the treasure is real, the box is sealed, and everyone has signed the permission slips before they let anyone touch the loot.\n\nSo, you'll likely get a letter from your lawyer or the title company telling you which specific escrow agent to contact. They will set up the account, hold your deposit and the down payment, and only release the money to the seller once the deed is officially transferred. It's a crucial step to ensure that when you sign the final papers, the money is actually there and the house is actually yours.\n\nIf you try to skip this and just mail the check yourself, you might find yourself in a situation where the seller has already sold the house to someone else,",
      "source": "target",
